k and the queer, Hubbs challenges the conventional wisdom and historical amnesia that frame white working folk as a perpetual bigot class. With a powerful combination of music criticism, cultural critique, and sociological analysis of contemporary class formation, Nadine Hubbs zeroes in on flawed assumptions about how country music models and mirrors white working-class identities. She particularly shows how dismissive, politically loaded middle-class discourses devalue country’s manifestations of working-class culture, politics, and values, and render working-class acceptance of queerness invisible. Lucid, important, and thought-provoking, this book is essential reading for students and scholars of American music, gender and sexuality, class, and pop culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCountry musicxHistory and criticism. 0aCountry musicxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aHomosexuality and popular musiczUnited States. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aamerican bigotry.  aanthropologist.  aawareness.  aclass and gender identity.  aclass formation.  acommunity activism.  acountry music and homosexuality.  acultural anthropology.  ahistorical inquiry.  ahomophobia.  algbt.  algbtqia rights leader.  amiddle-class americans.  amusical criticism.  apolitically charged music.  apopular music.  asexual identity.  asocial activist.  asociological analysis.  aworking class bigot.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028065640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095834040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958340423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958340/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d201